  "texts": [
    "Relatedly, we might want to know what parts of that world are bound up in the processes structured by rational norms and directed towards intentional ends.",
    "In other words, we might wonder how and where these features (or seeming features) enter the picture.",
    "HEC suggests that we should answer these questions in a way that emphasises the role played by cognitive agent's bodies and environments -as well as processes internal to their brains -in producing a world populated by genuine cognizors.",
    "Drawing from an older tradition of 'externalism' in philosophy of mind, HEC's early supporters argued that not only the contents but also the realisers of cognition, thought, and reasoning \"just ain't in the head\" (Putnam, 1975; see, e.g., Clark & Chalmers, 1998; Hurley, 1998).",
    "Part of what motivates externalism in philosophy of mind are problems that arise when some phenomenon resists explanation in terms that mention only the individual who is supposed to realise or exhibit the phenomenon."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Drawing from an older tradition of 'externalism' in philosophy of mind, HEC's early supporters argued that not only the contents but also the realisers of cognition, thought, and reasoning \"just ain't in the head\" (Putnam, 1975; see, e.g., Clark & Chalmers, 1998; Hurley, 1998)."
  ]
